article.description: New Mexico drilled 13 3-pointers en route to an upset of LaToya Thomas and Mississippi State.
article.headline: New Mexico steps back for second-ever tourney win
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- New Mexico center Jordan Adams posted
up behind the 3-point line and put up a shot that seemed to have no
chance.

	   The ball hit the front of the rim, bounced halfway up on the
backboard, came back down on the rim for another bounce, and then
rolled gently into the net.

	   Adams' early 3-pointer Monday was a huge clue that the
Mississippi State Lady Bulldogs were in for a long night and that
New Mexico was headed for a momentous win.

	   Adams went on to score 19 points and the sixth-seeded Lobos hit
13 3-pointers in a 73-61 win over third-seed Mississippi State in
the second round of the Midwest Regional.

	   It's the school's biggest victory ever in women's basketball and
sends the Lobos (24-8) into the round of 16.

	   But they're not going far.

	   New Mexico is hosting the first four rounds in the Midwest, so
the Lobos will be home again when they play the winner of Tuesday's
Texas-Tech-UC-Santa Barbara game. Before its 91-85 overtime win
over Miami on Saturday, New Mexico had never won a game in the NCAA
tournament.

	   It's a sure thing that The Pit will again be sold out, as New
Mexico's women continue to treat their fans to March Madness.
They've now accomplished what the men's program has never been able
to do -- win back-to-back games in the NCAA tournament.

	   "I've become a women's basketball fan,'' said New Mexico Gov.
Bill Richardson, who watched the game from a prime seat near
midcourt. "This is my sixth game and I think I have more fun at
women's basketball than at the men's games.''

	   Jordan's unlikely 3-pointer three minutes into the game was the
Lobos' fourth of the game and by then the No. 13 ranked Lady
Bulldogs were looking more like underdogs.

	   New Mexico stunned Mississippi State (24-8) early by hitting
their first 6 3-pointers and 10 of their first 12 shots. New
Mexico, playing on its homecourt before a frenzied sellout crowd of
16,214, hit 9 3s in the first half.

	   "If you can get the 3s going, it opens up the inside,'' said
Moore, who hit 5 3-pointers and now has 9 in the tournament. "You
could see we were much more relaxed.''

	   New Mexico had trouble scoring early against Miami, but this
time played like a team that could make a deep run into the
tournament.

	   "We scored early and scored often,'' coach Don Flanagan said.
"We weren't stopping them, but they certainly weren't stopping us
either.''

	   Mississippi State coach Sharon Fanning said her team wasn't
ready to play.

	   "I'm very disappointed of our team defense. That's what got us
here, defense, rebounding the ball and taking good shots,'' Fanning
said.

	   "They came out ready to play,'' MSU guard Tan White said.
"Everytime we'd come back, they'd hit another three.''

	   Eight straight points by New Mexico, on a layup by Adams and
back-to-back 3s by Moore and Lindsey Arndt gave the Lobos a 36-22
lead with 4:54 left in the first half. Moore finished with 19
points, including five 3-pointers.

	   All-American LaToya Thomas scored 29 points and had 16 rebounds
to lead the Lady Bulldogs, while White finished with 17 points and
9 rebounds.

	   The two led the Lady Bulldogs on an 8-2 run early in the second
half that cut the deficit to 43-38 with 16:54 left.

	   Adams halted that rally with a short jumper that kicked off a
16-5 run that put away the Lady Bulldogs. Reserves Melissa Forest
and Abbie Letz had 3-pointers in the run, the latter making it
59-43 with 11:44 left.

	   The 6-foot-3 Adams also had 10 rebounds and 5 blocks and became
the school's all-time shot blocker for men's and women's
basketball. Her career total of 341 is five more than former New
Mexico center Luc Longley.

	   Adams blocked the 6-foot-2 Thomas twice in the second half, the
first one sending the ball five rows into the stands.

	   Not only did the Lobos' shooting get to the Lady Bulldogs, so
did the mile-high altitude. A winded Thomas several times checked
herself out of the game and the other Mississippi State players had
trouble getting back on defense.

	   "It was hard running up and down the court for the past couple
of days and it was hard for us to adjust to the altitude,'' said a
tearful Thomas. "But we shouldn't have been fatigued like that. I
think we just gave up.''
